Fig. 5
 indicates CDs (a) and CDs/MEO (b) release curves at 284 nm and CDs/MEO at 277 nm, respectively, at various pH (1,2, 4.5, 7.4) cases. The release behavior of active ingredients from CDs at pH = 1.2 is faster than pH = 7.4 and pH = 4.5. Release of the active substance from CDs/MEO at pH = 1.2, 4.5 is slower than pH = 7.4, which released a high concentration during 8 h with the same stable time, based on the n value in the Korsmeyer- Peppas model, which is collected in more detail in (Table 4
), the release mechanism of CDs at pH = 1.2 and pH = 7.4 is controlled by Fick law (case I), the release of CDs at pH = 4.5 occurs by a combination of swelling and diffusion release. In the case of CDs/MEO, released in all pHs follows Fick law (case I). As a result, active CDs and CDs/MEO release are slower at pH = 4.5. Furthermore, the high release of CDs/MEO can be affected by the loading amount of M. piperita, which was calculated at 68%. In the case of smaller CDs great surface area produces a higher number of drug molecules at the surface of carbon dots ready for faster release.
